      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was caused by a systemic breakdown of the palatial redistributive economy triggered by a prolonged drought that simultaneously reduced agricultural yields across the Eastern Mediterranean, starving the specialized labor forces and bureaucracies that the palaces depended on.\", \"mechanism\": \"A multi-year drought (evidenced by paleoclimate proxies) reduced grain harvests. Palace economies, which collected, stored, and redistributed surplus to support scribes, artisans, soldiers, and dependent laborers, could no longer meet their obligations. This led to a rapid, cascading loss of legitimacy and administrative capacity, causing elites to hoard, subjects to flee, and the entire top-heavy system to implode in a short period.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Paleoclimate data shows no significant, synchronous multi-year drought across the Eastern Mediterranean in the late 13th/early 12th century BC.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows that palatial storage facilities were full of grain at the time of their destruction.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This account explains the simultaneity and selectivity of the collapse. Egypt survived because the Nile's annual flood was less dependent on local rainfall, buffering it against the drought that crippled rain-fed agricultural systems. The mechanism is a direct failure of the core economic institution (palatial redistribution) that defined these societies.\"}",
