      "content": "{\"claim\": \"The collapse was driven by a rapid, disruptive shift in military technology and tactics—the massed infantry assault—which rendered the elite chariot-based armies of the palace states obsolete and allowed internal or external infantry forces to overwhelm the palatial centers.\", \"mechanism\": \"The development of new infantry weapons (like the Naue II slashing sword) and tactics (massed shock troops) negated the battlefield dominance of the chariot. Chariots were the military expression of the palatial elite's power and a key tool for suppressing internal revolt and defending borders. When infantry forces (whether Sea Peoples, rural rebels, or neighboring tribes) could defeat chariot armies, the palaces lost their coercive grip and were sacked in quick succession.\", \"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"Mycenaean Greece\", \"Hittite Anatolia\", \"Ugarit\", \"Levantine city-states\"], \"excludes\": [\"Egypt\"]}, \"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Archaeological evidence shows that chariot use and production increased, not decreased, in the period immediately preceding the collapse.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}, {\"case\": \"The destruction layers at collapsed sites show no evidence of infantry-type weapons or battle tactics distinct from earlier periods.\", \"eval\": \"rubric:std-hist\"}], \"prose_notes\": \"This account explains the military defeats and burn layers. Egypt survived because it adapted quickly, integrating infantry (including Sherden mercenaries) into its forces and using its infantry-based army to defeat the Sea Peoples at the Battle of the Delta, as recorded at Medinet Habu.\"}",
